## 1 · Color System

The palette is **[N colors total]**. No others without explicit override.

### 1.1 Brand-core (use these in every video)

| Token | Hex | Role | Where it appears |
|-------|-----|------|------------------|
| `--primary-mid` | `#XXXXXX` | Primary brand hue, surfaces, italic-emphasis text | Cards, italic captions, ambient washes |
| `--primary-deep` | `#XXXXXX` | Card edges, drop shadows, 3D depth, secondary emphasis | Bevels, text on light backgrounds |
| `--primary-light` | `#XXXXXX` | Highlights, chrome sheen on cards, hover states | Diagonal sweep on every brand card |
| `--anchor-near-black` | `#XXXXXX` | Structural type, the anchor color | Headers, CTA verbs, body emphasis |
| `--background-paper` | `#XXXXXX` | Default background | All non-brand-color scenes |

**Reference example palette (sage-default - replace with yours):**
```css
--primary-mid:        #6a9e88;
--primary-deep:       #3f6b58;
--primary-light:      #a8d9c2;
--anchor-near-black:  #1f3a2c;
--background-paper:   #f0ece5;
```

### 1.2 Accent (use sparingly - earned, never decorative)

| Token | Hex | Role | When to use |
|-------|-----|------|-------------|
| `--accent-warm` | `#XXXXXX` | Premium / urgency / "the exception" | One-row color-break in numbered lists. Single emphasis word per video for "the punchline." Never two accent elements simultaneously. |
| `--accent-alert` | `#XXXXXX` | Active / alert / system-state highlight | Sidebar bands in fake UI. At most one per video. |

**Reference example accents:**
```css
--accent-warm:  #c8843a;
--accent-alert: #e8a591;
```

### 1.3 Discipline rules

- **Brand-core family + paper background = ~90% of every frame.** Foreign-brand surfaces (real product logos like Notion purple, Figma orange) earn their place by being a real product the script names.
- **Never inject a color "because it looks nice."** Each color carries one meaning.
- **Foreign-brand colors are imported, not invented.** Don't tint real product logos to match your brand.
- **No neon, no fluorescent** unless your essence calls for it explicitly.
- **Pure black is too cold against warm-paper backgrounds.** Use `--anchor-near-black` instead.

---

## 2 · Type System

Two type voices. They are non-negotiable. No third voice without explicit override.

### 2.1 Voice A — Structural

- **Family:** [your structural type family - e.g. classical display serif, geometric sans, slab serif]
  - Reference example: Recoleta Bold, Eames Century Modern Bold, Caslon Display Bold, Playfair Display Bold all read correctly for a sage-default brand
- **Color:** `--anchor-near-black`
- **Weight:** Bold (700)
- **Treatment:** [optional - drop shadow, kerning, etc.]
- **Used for:** section headers, structural words, CTA verbs, masthead labels

### 2.2 Voice B — Emphasis

- **Family:** [emphasis variant of Voice A - usually italic of the same family]
- **Color:** `--primary-mid`
- **Weight:** Regular italic
- **Used for:** the *emphasis* word inside a header pair, italic captions

### 2.3 Voice C — UI mono (in-product overlays only)

- **Family:** [mono family - Geist Mono, JetBrains Mono, Roboto Mono]
- **Color:** `--anchor-near-black` on light, `--primary-light` on dark
- **Used for:** code blocks, JSON in scraping demos, app sidebar labels in fake-UI surfaces
- **Never** for narration captions

### 2.4 Caption type (the spoken word on screen)

- **Family:** [your caption family - Voice A italic for editorial brands, heavy sans for ad-register brands]
- **Color:** [your caption color - white on a tinted pill, or single-emphasis-word color over speaker]
- **Single emphasis word per caption** - the rest stay neutral

### 2.5 Type discipline rules

- **No grotesque / geometric sans** if your essence is editorial. Inter / Helvetica / SF Pro / Geist Sans break editorial register.
- **No Montserrat** for any role unless your brand calls for it. Reads "lifestyle blog" by default.
- **Italics earn their place.** Italic = emphasis or contrast. Don't italicize a whole sentence.
- **Type sizes are aggressive.** Hero title cards run 96-160px. Section labels at 32-48px. Captions at 56-72px.

---

## 3 · Speaker Treatment (when face is shown)

### 3.1 The grading rule

Decide your stance: **naturally graded** or **stylized**? The two big options:

- **Naturally graded** (editorial-magazine and screen-face-split default) - keep the speaker's real environment, real lighting, real skin tones. Mild warm bias OK. The "I just sat down to film this" energy is the trust device.
- **Stylized / desaturated** (sage-stack default for the original Greg Isenberg reference; modern-creator brands tend to invert this and stay naturally graded instead) - the speaker is a B-roll element, the graphics carry color.

Most modern creators run naturally-graded because heavy grading reads as "AI-bro reel" by default. Choose deliberately.

### 3.2 Framing rule

- Chest-up, head-anchor stable, mic visible bottom-right (or just out of frame)
- Centered horizontally
- Eyeline locked center

---

## 4 · Texture

- **Grain overlay** at low opacity (~3-4%) on every scene - ties everything together
- **Paper texture** for B-roll-only scenes (if your brand uses paper)
- **No glossy gradients, no neon glows, no chromatic aberration** as a brand-default unless your essence calls for them

---

## 5 · Motion / Transitions

This file does not own motion - each archetype's `STYLE_DECON.md` does. But two cross-cutting brand rules:

1. **Bouncy / elastic easing yes/no** - default no for editorial brands, yes for playful brands.
2. **Hard cuts vs. whip-blurs** - default rule, archetypes can override.

